05413nam a22007935i 9781782382355DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013022200  a97817823823557 a10.1515/97817823823552doi  a(DE-B1597)636291  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHV6545b.C786 2014 4aHV6545 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a362.2800aCulture, Suicide, and the Human Condition /ced. by Marja-Liisa Honkasalo, Miira Tuominen. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (230 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Varieties of Suicide: Inquiring into the Complexity of Human Experience -- tPart I Suicide: Cross-Cultural Perspectives -- tChapter 1 The Construction of the Suicidal Self in Phenomenological Psychology -- tChapter 2 When It Is Worth the Trouble to Die: The Cultural Valuation of Suicide -- tPart II Ancient and Medieval Approaches to Suicide -- tChapter 3 “Tell Him to Follow Me as Quickly as Possible” Plato’s Phaedo (60c–63c) on Taking One’s Own Life -- tChapter 4 Free Philosophers and Tragic Women: Stoic Perspectives on Suicide -- tChapter 5 Moral Philosophical Arguments against Suicide in the Middle Ages -- tPart III Morality, Politics, and Violence: Suicide in Contemporary Societies -- tChapter 6 “She Kissed Death with a Smile” The Politics and Moralities of the Female Suicide Bomber -- tChapter 7 “When We Stop Living, We Also Stop Dying” Men, Suicide, and Moral Agency -- tAfterword -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSuicide is a puzzling phenomenon. Not only is its demarcation problematic but it also eludes simple explanation. The cultures in which suicide mortality is high do not necessarily have much else in common, and neither is a single mental illness such as depression sufficient to lead a person to suicide. In a word, despite its statistical regularity, suicide is unpredictable on the individual level. The main argument emerging from this collection is that suicide should not be understood as a separate realm of pathological behavior but as a form of human action. As such it is always dependent on the decision that the individual makes in a cultural, ethical and socio-economic context, but the context never completely determines the decision. This book also argues that cultural narratives concerning suicide have a problematic double function: in addition to enabling the community to make sense of self-inflicted death, they also constitute a blueprint depicting suicide as a solution to common human problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aSuicidexPhilosophy. 0aSuicidexSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCátedra, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlgren, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrahn, Malin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonkasalo, Marja-Liisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonkasalo, Marja-Liisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKleinman, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacdonald, Charles J.-H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMäkinen, Virpi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaudin, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuominen, Miira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuominen, Miira, eeditor.4edt4http://i